         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">25, WILTON PLACE, S.W. ¶ Nov 17/67 ¶ My dear Sir ¶  ¶ I was much pleased to learn by your last letter that you found yourself much better for your visit to Queens Cliff Mr Wilson ¶  whom I met the oth...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">67.11.17</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M4, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg rend="form%20text" style="color: #2f5496; font-family: Times; ">25, WILTON PLACE, S.W.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Nov 17/67<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS annotation at top of letter in M's hand: 'Niemeyera'.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I was much pleased to learn by your last letter that you found yourself much better for your visit to Queens Cliff Mr Wilson<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Edward Wilson?</p>
               </note> whom I met the other day at a dinner party tells me that he also has heard better accounts of you — I trust that you have now quite recovered your usual health and that you will not overwork yourself.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The whole of the plants you announce as having sent off have arrived safely, those per Great Britain first and per Sussex a few days after. I hope that the remainder of <name key="Monopetalae">Monopetalae</name> may be on their way ere this reaches you</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In one of your letters you speak of several of Drummonds nos not being quoted by me,<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M to G. Bentham, 26 March 1867 (in this edition as 67-03-26a).</p>
               </note> the reason is that these numbers are very irregularly preserved in the Hookerian herbarium which has the most complete set. The first collection was distributed in the first instance as sent over here without numbers, of this I see numerous specimens from the Hookerian, my own, Lindley's and other herbaria, corresponding specimens were afterwards sent with numbers which were not regularly entered in the herbaria which had them without numbers — then came successively the 2d 3d 4th 5th and 6th collections and various supplements all separately numbered and often in Sir William's<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Sir William Hooker.</p>
               </note> set not numbered so that there is always the greatest uncertainty about the numbering and I once thought of not giving the numbers at all for fear of leading into error — sometimes also the numbers badly written have been misread and erroneously copied.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am very steadily at work at the Flora.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bentham (1863-78), vol. 4.</p>
               </note> Since I wrote I have finished <name key="Campanulaceae">Campanulaceae</name> (<name key="Lobelia">Lobelia</name> 18 sp. <name key="Pratia">Pratia</name> 6 sp. <name key="Isotoma">Isotoma</name> 6 sp. <name key="Wahlenbergia">Wahlenbergia</name> 2 sp.) <name key="Scaevola">Scaevola</name>, 48 sp. and some small genera and nearly finished Goodenia. De Vriese's monograph is I agree with you the worst I ever met with and if I had not before me authentic specimens of the majority of his species I never could have made them out. In Hooker's collection which he had to work open he has given one name to five species belonging to three natural Orders. His generic characters sometimes belong to only a small portion of the species he puts under them. He quotes the same specimen for two different species — Describes one plant and figures another etc etc.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Vriese (1854). See M to G. Bentham, 21 April 1867 (in this edition as 67-04-21b).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>There are only two or three of Brown's which appear not to be in your collection<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">R. Brown (1810), pp. 574-590.</p>
               </note>
               <name key="Goodenia%20pumilio">Goodenia pumilio</name> a curious little plant which we have also from Cunningham and I do not think you have G. coronopifolia G. glabra Br. is G. flagellifera De Vr.<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">De Vriese.</p>
               </note> G. viscidula<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">G. viscida</seg>?</p>
               </note> Br is your G. spicata (at least for the look, I have not yet examined it)</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am afraid I shall have to make a genus<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bentham erected <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Catospermum</seg> (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">C. muelleri</seg>) in <seg style="">J. Hooker (1867-89), vol.</seg> 11, p. 20, t. 1028.</p>
               </note> for your <name key="Scaevola%20goodeniacea">Scaevola goodeniacea</name>, the ovary is so very exceptional there are 1 or 2 ovules in each cell <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">pendulous</hi>
               </seg> from the apex of the cavity, whilst in all <name key="Goodeniaceae">Goodeniaceae</name> I have as yet gone through they are erect I do not like monotypic genera and so I wait to decide till I have gone through all the little genera — If I find it really so exceptional I shall have it figured for Hooker's Icones which is now going on — the first part of the new Series is just out.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am very glad to hear you have a collector in Arnhem's Land.<note xml:id="ftn11" type="footnote" n="11">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Benjamin Guilliver, who accompanied Francis Cadell's exploring expedition.</p>
               </note> We want much <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">good</hi>
               </seg> specimens of tropical and Central Australian plants to test the value of numerous species necessarily founded on single fragments.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Ever yours sincerely</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>George Bentham</p>
